# Qwen2.5-Coder-7B direct-to-hero SWE-HERO SFT recipe.
#
# This preset carries the paper-faithful training configuration that used to
# live in launcher defaults. Keep experiment changes in a copied preset and
# use normal CLI flags after the preset for one-off overrides.
#
# SFT means "supervised fine-tuning": the model is trained to imitate accepted
# OpenHands assistant actions from SWE-HERO traces. "Direct-to-hero" means this
# run skips an intermediate SWE-ZERO stage and trains directly on SWE-HERO-style
# repository-editing trajectories. Every ML choice below is explicit so a run
# can be reproduced from this file plus the command line.

# Base checkpoint. The model id selects the public Qwen coding assistant, while
# the revision pins the exact Hugging Face snapshot. Pinning the revision matters
# because tokenizer files, chat templates, and model weights can change under the
# same model name and would change the training target.
--model-id Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct
--model-revision c03e6d358207e414f1eca0bb1891e29f1db0e242

# Training data. The local artifact is the project's public approximation of
# the SWE-HERO paper data: one accepted OpenHands rollout per SWE-bench task.
# The source dataset and revision are recorded so the local artifact can be
# rebuilt and audited instead of becoming an unexplained Parquet folder.
--dataset-id swe-hero-openhands-trajectories-5b2ed21-one-rollout
--source-dataset-id nvidia/SWE-Hero-openhands-trajectories
--source-dataset-revision 5b2ed21270ad773a50163e2999c510f0cbb92cfa

# Dataset materialization controls. Building if missing keeps pod launches
# self-contained, while the shard/batch sizes bound memory use when streaming the
# public source data and selecting the paper-like one-rollout artifact.
--build-dataset-if-missing
--source-dataset-rows-per-shard 2048
--source-dataset-build-batch-size 64

# Example limits. A zero value means "no artificial cap" for the production
# recipe. Smoke tests override these values instead of editing this preset.
--num-examples 0
--max-streamed-examples 0

# Sampling and sequence length. The model learns from long agent traces where
# earlier observations can affect later edits, so the production recipe trains
# with a 131,072-token context. The source artifact has already filtered out
# rows that do not fit this window, so a too-long example is treated as a data
# bug rather than silently truncated.
--shuffle-buffer 2048
--seed 17
--max-length 131072
--long-example-policy error

# Bucketed training. Long-context batches waste memory if every trace is padded
# to 128k tokens. Buckets group examples by length, then context parallelism
# ("CP") splits the token dimension across GPUs for the longer buckets. The
# short-to-long curriculum starts with cheaper 32k examples before exercising the
# full 128k path.
--buckets 32768,65536,131072
--bucket-curriculum short-to-long
--bucket-cp 32768:2,65536:4,131072:8

# Loss guard. The dataloader masks non-target tokens such as user messages and
# tool observations; at least one trainable assistant token must remain or the
# batch would contribute no learning signal.
--min-trainable-tokens 1

# Optimization schedule. Three epochs, batch size 32, and a small 1e-5 learning
# rate are conservative SFT settings for adapting a pretrained coding model
# without aggressively overwriting its base capabilities. Warmup ramps the
# learning rate from near-zero to avoid unstable early updates; min LR keeps the
# cosine/decay tail nonzero.
--num-train-epochs 3
--max-steps 0
--global-batch-size 32
--local-batch-size 1
--learning-rate 1e-5
--min-learning-rate 1e-8
--warmup-ratio 0.1
--weight-decay 0.0

# Update stability. Gradient clipping limits rare large updates from very long
# traces. The foreach optimizer implementation uses PyTorch's batched tensor
# update path, which is faster without changing the optimizer math.
--max-grad-norm 1.0
--optimizer-impl foreach

# Compute and memory strategy. SDPA uses PyTorch's scaled-dot-product attention
# backend. FP8 rowwise communication/storage, bfloat16 mixed precision, full
# activation checkpointing, and chunked cross-entropy all reduce memory pressure
# enough to make 128k-token SFT feasible on one 8xH100 pod. The training loss is
# still accumulated in float32 to keep the scalar optimization signal stable.
--attention-backend sdpa
--enable-fp8
--fp8-recipe rowwise
--compile
--training-dtype float32
--mixed-precision-param-dtype bfloat16
--mixed-precision-reduce-dtype bfloat16
--fsdp-reshard-after-forward never
--activation-checkpoint-mode full
--chunked-ce-chunks 8

# Checkpointing. Frequent async checkpoints are expensive but important for long
# GPU jobs: they reduce lost work after interruption and the first-step check
# verifies checkpoint/resume mechanics before a production run has burned hours.
--checkpoint-interval 25
--checkpoint-async-mode async
--validate-first-step-checkpoint

# Log every step because production jobs are few and expensive; sparse metrics
# would make it harder to diagnose loss spikes, throughput drops, or hangs.
--metrics-log-freq 1

# Pod preflight resource gates. These fail before distributed training starts if
# the shared GPU pod lacks enough disk, GPU memory, CPU memory, or write
# throughput for checkpoints and long-context activations.
--min-free-disk-gb 100
--min-free-gpu-memory-gb 60
--min-free-cpu-memory-gb 32
--min-write-throughput-mb-s 50
--write-throughput-probe-mb 64

# Profiling defaults. The production recipe leaves profiler and memory snapshots
# off because they add overhead and large artifacts. The trace settings stay here
# so an operator can enable profiling with one CLI flag while preserving the same
# model/data recipe.
--no-enable-profiler
--profiler-trace-folder profiling/traces
--profiler-freq 10
--profiler-active 1
--profiler-warmup 3
--no-enable-memory-snapshot
--memory-snapshot-folder profiling/memory_snapshot

# Distributed launch topology. One pod owns all eight local GPUs, so torchrun
# launches eight local ranks and uses a local c10d rendezvous. NCCL async error
# handling helps fail the job promptly when one rank/GPU encounters a transport
# problem instead of leaving the remaining ranks hung.
--nproc-per-node 8
--nnodes 1
--node-rank 0
--rdzv-backend c10d
--rdzv-endpoint localhost:0
--rdzv-id ""
--log-rank 0
--torchrun-log-rank-filter 0
--cuda-device-max-connections 1
--torch-nccl-async-error-handling 1

# Safety mode. The canonical preset defaults to non-production so smoke and dry
# runs cannot be confused with the paper-aligned production run. Real production
# launches opt in with CLI flags after this preset.
--no-production-mode
--no-production-acceptance-smoke
